### Seven-Segment Display Values Explained

The display register (`display_out`) is a 32-bit value. The seven-segment controller takes `display_out[4:0]` (lowest 5 bits) and shows it as a two-digit decimal number on **AN3** (tens) and **AN2** (ones) — the leftmost two digits on your board.

| Step | display_out (hex) | bits[4:0] | Decimal | AN3 (tens) | AN2 (ones) |
|------|-------------------|-----------|---------|------------|------------|
| 1 | 0x00005003 | 00011 | 3 | **0** | **3** |
| 2 | 0x00000001 | 00001 | 1 | **0** | **1** |
| 3 | 0x00000000 | 00000 | 0 | **0** | **0** |
| 4 | 0x00000001 | 00001 | 1 | **0** | **1** |
| 5 | 0x00000002 | 00010 | 2 | **0** | **2** |

> [!NOTE]
> For Step 1 (LUI), the full value is 0x5003 but the 7-seg only shows the lower 5 bits = 3. The **LEDs** are what prove the upper bits (LED 14 and 12 = bits 14 and 12 of 0x5000). The 7-seg and LEDs work together to show the full picture.

